post_text:
Northwood Community,
I want to start by thanking all of you who have reached out to ask questions and get clarity on our current reopening plan. I am devastated that we will not reopen 5 days, but appreciate all who are understanding the impossible situation we are facing. As my own family decides how to handle having our three children at home 3 days each week, I know many are struggling with that planning as well. This is not easy and we acknowledge that.
I want to take a minute to remind everyone that as a district and community we need to be able to support our fellow parents. I have watched as social media has descended into arguments and name calling in the comment sections of‚Ä¶ More

post_text:
2 weeks from today our school year begins. Our staff returns Thursday, August 13 to prepare for this school year. The last time we had classes in our building was Friday, March 13. It has been 5 months. Hybrid plan is by no means ideal, but having half of our students each day is better than none.

Our Open House originally scheduled for August 13 must be cancelled. However, we are working on a plan for a virtual open house to allow parents and students to see the buidling, their teachers, their classrooms and our safety protocols. Look for more information from your Principal very soon!

Email Mrs Krontz or Mr. Johnson with questions:
lkrontz@northwoodschools.org (Grades PK-6)
ejohnson@northwoodschools.org (Grades 7-12)

#RangerStrong #MasksOnOhio

shared_text:
Northwood Music Department
June 15 at 9:01 PM ¬∑

Band Camp update #1

Continue keeping the July 27th-31st dates available for band camp with the performance on the 31st. I am working closely with administration and local health officials to determine the best way we can conduct a safe camp for students. We are planning on having a band camp during those days. Exactly what that band camp will look like will depend on the upcoming weeks. We have several plans prepared, but may need a completely different one. The exact schedule and plan will be released closer to the band camp dates. I wish I could give more information right now, but with how quickly our situation has been changing we will not know what guidelines will look like in 6-7 weeks. I assure you we will do everything we can to be safe and smart about our return to marching band. Stay tuned for more updates in the upcoming weeks. I hope you are enjoying your summer and as always happy practicing!

Mr. Shirey

Northwood Track
June 3 at 7:46 PM ¬∑

Summer Training Update:
As many of you already know, the schools have opened back up our facilities for summer training. However, this is on a very limited availability of time and space. So we, as the track coaches, are unfortunately not going to begin summer workouts yet. We are going to let the sports who have seasons coming up this fall figure out their schedules for the weight room and building facilities before we begin to schedule ours. We will revisit the schedule later in the summer and announce when our training sessions will begin. We will keep posting workouts for those who want to continue to workout from home. If you would like to go into the weight room, you can contact Coach Lewin or Coach James to sign up for a time slot.

Today we want to recognize our cafeteria staff and bus drivers, who have been packing lunches and making deliveries since we closed in March. Following today's final delivery they have surpassed 22,000 lunch deliveries during this closure. Yes, 22,000!

Food Service Staff: Terri Russell, Ginger Cairl, Angel Grey, Cindy McWatters, Julie Phelps, Mitzi Reighard, Kenda St. John & Erin Wauford along with supervisor Emilia Bires.

Bus Drivers: Jack Didion, Tracy Gribble, Beth Hanthorn, Pat Hanthorn, Heather Mickens, Maddeline Moore, Jami Murray, Letha Scott, Tom Siglar, Jennifer Stewart & Jennifer Vollmar along with supervisor Greg Hornstein.

Thank you all!

Parents,

Today marks our 37th virtual school day since we began on March 17. We have 8 more to go before the end of the school year. I continue to thank you and our staff for your efforts through what will end up being 10 weeks of school closure to end our year. I have heard so many great stories of student/teacher interaction, but I have also heard stories of students who have increasingly become less engaged. This is one of the biggest concerns with the coming months and the uncertainty for the 2020-2021 school year. We hope to know more in the coming weeks about the parameters that will be required for next school year, but right now we do not have many answers. We know we have‚Ä¶ More

A MESSAGE FROMTHE WOOD COUNTY DISTRICT PUBLIC LIBRARY:

Lynda.com and Ohio libraries are working together so you can learn from home. Thanks to an agreement between the Ohio Public Library Information Network (OPLIN) and LinkedIn, WCDPL joins Ohio's libraries in offering lynda.com free to library cardholders.

Lynda is an online training service that provides access to thousands of online courses on everything from computer programming to podcasting to web design. Start from the library's website, https://wcdpl.org/lyndacom. Please note that if you skip the library's website and go directly to Lynda.com, you will be prompted to purchase a subscription, so be sure to start on the library's link above.

After logging in with your library barcode, you must create a personalized lynda.com account by entering your name and e-mail address. This account helps you manage your course history, playlists, bookmarks, and Certificates of Completion. Temporary cards won't work on Lynda.com, so if you need help getting your library card details, be sure to contact us by email or by chat.

Lynda.com | Wood County District Public Library

post_text:
A message from the Wood County Public Library:

As screen time increases during learning from home, families and students may be looking for inspiration for non-digital activities. The Hobbies and Crafts Reference Center offers detailed "how-to" instructions and creative ideas to meet the interests of virtually every family. Watch origami videos, learn to draw, or learn about amateur HAM Radio with over 720 videos, and 180 hobby profiles with instructions. There are even specific sections for Kids' Crafts and for Science and Technology with information on robotics.

Follow this link (https://wcdpl.org/reference) and then click on "H." Scroll down to Hobbies and Crafts Reference Center. You will need your library card number for the final step, and if you need an immediate-access library card you can get one at this link: https://wcdpl.org/temporary-library-account. Stay well and see what creative things your library can help you make!

post_text:
The Covid-19 Crisis is affecting people worldwide and the Wood County District Public Library can help families with a global perspective through access to newspapers from around the globe. Access World Book Online and read how we are truly all in this together! Many of the papers offer English language versions, but for language students, the resource also offers valuable language practice in most world languages.

It takes some clicking, but the reward is worth it! From this webpage, https://wcdpl.org/reference select "W" and scroll down to World Book Online. On the World Book landing page select the box for Advanced. On the next screen, leave the search box empty and select "Advanced Search. " Then click on the "Take me to" box and look for World Newspapers in the drop-down menu.

This resource is available with an Ohio library card and if families need an immediate-access library card, those are available on our website at https://wcdpl.org/temporary-library-account

The Science Reference Center, with hundreds of science magazines, encyclopedias, reference books and a vast collection of images, is available under Homework Help at this link: https://www.ohioweblibrary.org/sources/. The source also includes the Science Image Collection, a database of high-quality science images from National Geographic, UPI, Getty, NASA and Nature Picture Library. There‚Ä¶

Yesterday was a day that our staff greatly enjoyed. We had over 70 staff members who were able to make it in for the parade around town. They split into 2 groups to reach as many streets as possible on each side of town, and while we know we did not make it to every single street and every single house, we know it was a great feeling for the staff to see so many students to say we miss you. I am incredibly proud of our staff and our students during this time as they work together to make the best of a terrible situation. The maps pictured are NOT exact routes, but rather a basic description of the direction we will travel. The Northwood Police Department will be leading the parades and because we are breaking into 2 groups, we will travel as many streets as we can to see as many students as possible. Unfortunately we cannot get to every single street, but we hope to see many of our Rangers! We plan to leave the school parking lot at 4pm. Thanks to the NPD for helping! #TheRangerWay

A message from the Wood County District Public Library:

Wood County District Public Library and Gale, an information and learning resources leader for more than 65 years, have made a number of Gale's most comprehensive digital educational resources available free from home during the COVID-19 pandemic crisis.

Ten modules are available that provide learning-focused resources to maintain academic continuity from home and credible research on timely topics related to health and global issues.

The entire package covers students from kindergarten through college and can be found on the Wood County District Public Library's webpage at https://wcdpl.org/free-educational-support-gale.

post_text:
Parents,

This week's update is one I knew was coming, but really was dreading sending out. Our school closure has been extended to Friday, May 1st at which time the Governor will reassess the situation and decide if we return to school in May. Even though it is the right decision, it certainly is not what we wanted to hear. Once again, we know you did not sign up for this, but we are going to need to continue to work together to make the best of this situation.

I sincerely hope everyone in your family is healthy and safe. Please reach out to us if there is anything we might be able to help with during this time. We may be able to connect you with resources or just get you the contact‚Ä¶

We want to congratulate Austin Cole on his career and share some of his achievements.

2x State Qualifier
3x league champion

Career record for pins - 81
2nd all time career wins - 134
4th all time takedowns -240
2nd all time 2 point nearfall - 72
5th all time 3 point nearfall - 78
3rd all time tech fall -12
21 tournament places
9 championships

post_text:
Parents,

As we head into the final day of our "Spring Break" week I wanted to provide an update as we look to next week and potentially beyond.
Virtual school work resumes next week March 30-April 3

We plan to continue our lunch deliveries with a few changes:
We will deliver 2 lunches on Mondays
We will deliver 3 lunches on Wednesday
We will not deliver on Tuesday/Thursday/Friday
This will continue our lunch delivery service while allowing our staff to work minimal hours and maintain safety.

The Governor has only closed school through April 3, but we expect this to be extended. We do not know when he will make that decision. In yesterday's press conference he was not ready to make that‚Ä¶

post_text:
It is a wonderful feeling when your entire staff comes together to try and provide the best possible services they can in a time of uncertainty for our students and families. I am so thankful for our staff and their efforts these past few days. I am so thankful for the teachers working today to find more and more resources.

Many people outside of our school are also facing adversity within our own community. We must come together and be there to support each other as best we can. Look for continued communication in the coming days and weeks. Let us know as a school what you need and we will try to connect services wherever we can.

Thank you to our amazing staff!

Jason Kozina
Superintendent

Parents,

Today the Governor announced in response to COVID-19 what he called an "Extended Spring Break" for 3 weeks. We are seeking guidance from the Ohio Department of Education about our requirements during this time period. The Governor said they would reassess the situation following that 3 week period. This would begin at the end of the day on Monday, March 16.
We will be in session tomorrow Friday, March 13.
We will use Monday as a Professional Development day for staff only.
Students will not report on Monday, March 16. Penta students will need to follow Penta's plan for Monday.
We will reassess the situation prior to Monday, April 6
There will be NO activities, practices or‚Ä¶ More

Another busy week!
Music Booster meeting @7pm, Monday, in the HS Music Room

7th-12th Grade Band Concert @7pm, Wednesday, at the AAA Auditiorum

Performance is open to the public. OMEA has strict policies regarding electronic devices at Adjudicated Events.
